snippet.textDisplay:
Ugggh...I have spent an inordinate amount of my time over the last few weeks fielding questions from the general public relating to the various "health products" that have cropped up due to the COVID-19 outbreak.

Whenever you see a product that makes any claims relating to improving health or nutrition, just check to see if there's any actual research that's looked for significant effects. A double-blind randomized control trial is best, but those are rare for foods.

If all you can find are endorsements from blogs, or organizations like Natural News, they probably won't offer any benefit...and could even be harmful. There's already been a tragic example of this due to some...exaggerated claims relating to chloroquine as a treatment for COVID-19.


It's promising, but the clinical studies are just beginning. Some have chosen not to wait, and have been instances of people buying algicides containing the drug...and being injured, or in one case killed as a result.

I’d like to see a taste testing show where you take things like different cheeses, and compare them to other comparable cheeses from different areas of the world famous / known for producing that product. Like compare an award winning 5 year old cheddar from England to an award winning 5 year old cheddar from Wisconsin. Stuff like that. You could do it with other stuff like wines, cured meat products, etc..

You could also perhaps take some of the products that technically can only be made in one place / have a “protected designation of origin” and compare them to equivalently priced imitation products from other areas. I’d be interested to see if the protected products are actually better.

I would love to try the dried peel stuff. As you say, its a good use of something tossed out. An alternative to snacking on way worse stuff - BUT if I ever get hold of any, I would dip them in dark chocolate! That might make them more interesting to more people? There is at least one sugar free melting chocolate - Cavalier gourmet melting chocolate (fibers, stevia and erythriol - not any of the sweeteres that usually make people fart and all that stuff!) is a great product if you dont want loads of sugar.

On a site note, as I was watching this I am eating a swedish, low sugar chocolate peanut bar from Nick's- If you can find these in the UK I would recommend you try! Also made with stevia and erytriol, I think. Again, I dont have any """Issues"""" after eating them ... They also make a milk chocolate powder that I really liked but I havent seen in here in Norway (for a while? unsure were I got it. We do shop a lot in Sweden.)

snippet.textDisplay: I'm amazed how people keep falling for those stupid things like superfoods. As for ginseng, only because something has been used by the Chinese or some other ancient culture for thousands of years doesn't mean it's good or does what it says it does. Usually, quite the opposite or, at least, not in any significant amount. And LOL, it's believed to stimulate sexual potency because the Chinese thought it was shaped like a penis. And one thing Nature doesn't work with is similarity, unlike we used (and sadly scientifically illiterate people still do) to think. Mandrake root won't make women fertile or men more potent because it "looks" like a naked woman. Likewise, the stars won't predict or dictate one's life because the universe was not made for us and they were not put in place by some fictitious deity to guide our lives. There is no "as below as it is above" in real life, only in people's ignorant imaginations.

snippet.textDisplay:
Number one food trend in my household: rice and legumes! Like five varieties of rice! Basmati, jasmine, whole grain, random cheap "long grain", and delicious delicious red rice. Aaall of the legumes! Lentils pack the most protein punch, but chickpeas are just bloody delicious! Black beans, white beans, kidney beans... Lentil tacos, chickpea stews, chillis and curries. Dried soy ground meat substitute frees up freezer space for frozen veggies, because I will not survive this if I can't have my broccoli damn it.

There's a lot of conflicting reports online re: what does and doesn't freeze well, so I'm trying to figure out how usable creme fraiche is post-freezing... Experiments are underway.

snippet.textDisplay:
What!!! That's not how ginseng colors work at all. The colors are a result of different ways of processing it.

White/tan is naturally dried
Red is steamed (older roots aren't destroyed as easily in this process)

https://www.dec.ny.gov/animals/7474.html

Color is also used to describe different varieties and species of ginseng, "Red Ginseng" is Asian Ginseng, or *Panax Ginseng*, and white is often (although not always) American Ginseng, or *Panax quinquefolius*. Other loosely related non-ginseng (*Panax*) species are often called different kinds of ginseng as well.

- A mildly peeved ecologist with a bit of botany background.
